    "As mentioned in the introduction, a population of SMBHBs is expected to generate a highly non-Gaussian, partially anisotropic and perhaps non-stationary signal.",
    "As we increase the timespan of our data, improve our instrumentation and combine more pulsars, the detailed properties of the signal will eventually reveal themselves in the data (e.g.",
    "Cornish & Sesana 2013; Taylor & Gair 2013; Taylor et al. 2020; Pol et al. 2022).",
    "While many early Universe signals are expected to be isotropic and Gaussian, noticeable exceptions exist, such as GWBs from bursts of cosmic strings.",
